spanGrp.span: `Q) `ok, you brother in law, as you know tell us how sohmyntin vill came to be Who estd this vill.'
To me sakhiat kong t kam wa tip dangchwa ka-ni ka-chnong sohmyntin hei-won dur wan ko Yi wa sein chnong hei-ni'
`as far as i know, the elders told me that the lady from the Pyrtuh clan estd a vill here, and before that they resided in jwai/jowai.'
Nga katkam wa tip o t, wa sein chnong t ka yong pyrtuh, neibhah kat i-por wa parom ki wa hh t ong ki ki-ni ki yong pyrtuh i-chwa chong ki-t ha jwai.
`it seems that there were two sisters, the youngest have no goddess, but the elder sist have goddess, the youngest ones stole away her sist's goddess.'
T m ki-t ki-bru sniawsar chipayu ki, t ka-t ka-khian ym yoh blai, t tooh ka-t ka-payu khian na ka-t ka-hh ya ka-t ka-blai.
`the youngest sister was driven away from jowai, then she came and resided in this vill.'
T dp nei-t chah beh na jwai t wan chong chnong chei-ni.
`Q) `and according to what you know how was it.'
t me yn kat hei-jingtip yong me kammon
`acc to what i knew they came from Mynso.'
To, nga yn kat kam wa tip o t ne ong ki wan ki na Mynso.
`of course from mynso, from mynso to jowai, from jowai they came here.'
Na mynso re mo, na mynso ha jwai, na jwai poi ki chei-ni.
`it seems there was a batlle at that time it continued till this vill.'
Wa sniaw wa nei-t lh ong ki wa lh thma ki ne, sniawdur t ya-thma ki chei-ni cha chnong sohmyntin se.
`after the battle they resided in this vill and those people were from the pyrtuh clan only.'
Dep nei-t t poi ki ha chnong sohmyntin sein chnong ki dooh ka-t ka-kur pyrtuh hi.

`then since there were only 'pyrtuh in that village they started having fear of how can they stay like that, how will there be marriage, the people can't get a partner for themselves from the same clan..'

Dep neit t kat da sah samen du chi kur kamt, t kam ong katt t tein noh ki s, sniaw chong syer chong duk i-t mo, kammon kit poi kha poi man da ki-ni ki-bru lh ym yoh kha yoh man, t ong noh ka-t ka-jing-tp tein ki-t syer ki mo
`since then they had this fear and they are also afraid to stay single.'
T nadooh ka-t ka-por kat dang m ka-t ka-jingsyer ka-jingtein, t ong ki lh samen u-chong t tein. Mo.

`therefore this village was named after this situation, samenten (which means afraid to be alone), and it was further recommend officially in writings as Sohmynting (sohmen or samen `alone and ting or ten or tieng 'afraid.'
T neibhah t i-daw ya ka-ni ka-chnong da khut pyrtuit ya ka da ka-samentein, e noh pyrtuit ha jingthoh Sohmyntin.
`sohmen means alone, ting means afraid, this village came to be known as Sohmynting since then. (for a pnar speaker its SamyntiN, for a khasi its Sohmynting).'
Sohmen t mut samen, ting mut wa ten, t se ong ki wan chong chnong t pyrtuit ka-ni ka-chnong toh samen toh ten, t sohmyntin.
`that's the reason this vill was named as so.'
ka-t toh ka-daw ka wa e pyrtuit ya ka-ni kachnong mo.
`Q) `What are the different types of people that resided in this vill..'
ki-yi de ki-jait chnong ki wa wan chong chnong katte'
`then the aliens that resided here later were the people from across the Myngot river.'
t hadien nei-t ki-sohchnong t ki-tai ki na chiliang myngot
che chwa ka-yi ka wa nyngkong s, wa sakhiet
ki wa nyngkong wa wan sohchnong
`I don't know much about that, ok you tell them if you know.'
T nga lh re tip bha i-yi i-t, to to pyn-bood da me la tip mi s.
`what i know is, the second aliens who came to reside in this vill was the Phawa clan, during that time my grandmother was back carried (like a baby).'
i-t t kat i-jingtip yong nga, jan ka wa ar wan sohchnong hei-ni yong phawa, kat i-por wa wan sohchnong ki he-i-ni t ka-t ka-beipun i dang bah ki ka dei-bah.
`after that then came the Nonghuloo clan, then the khasi people, acc to what i know from the older people.'
T dp yn t hadien nei-t, wan ki-ni ki-nonghuloo, dp yn t t wan ki-ni ki-khyriem, katkam jingtip yong nga parom ki wa hh s.
`ok now we know the people from different clans who came to be citizens of this vill later on.'
To i-e kattu t da tip i man wa ki-t ki wa yalok ki wan sohchnong t ka-t ka-jait kur mo.
`so this pyrtuh clan they said, it's the first to estd this vill, till this day the chief of this vill should always be appointed from this clan, is it true bro in law .'

t ka-ni ka-kur pyrtuh kat da ong ki man ka wa sein chnong nyngkong t toh hi mai kong man hadooh ki-ni ki-sngi lh man wa ya u-rangbah chnong t da ong bait ki man u-thung rangbah chnong ki da u-ni yong pyrtuh hi, toh hi kam t'
`yes it's true, till today the pyrtuh clan was respect by the people and they obey to appoint the chief from the pyrtuh clan.'
ha-o kam t hi ka-chnong yong i dang neh hi wa lh ki wa rim burom ki ya ka-kur pyrtuh wa katni lh man ko ngooh u-paidbah yong ka-chnong ya u-thung hi da u-wahh ong ka-kur pyrtuh.
`since then the honor was given to the pyrtuh clan, to elect a vill chief from the elders of the clan.'
Ong bait nadooh t i-por hi pa ya man ksoh ki ya ka-t ka-burom para i hi kam ong ka-burom kylliang mo, toh i u wa hh wa san t u-jied noh da ka-t ka-kur pyrtuh mo.
`so till now the elder from the pyrtuh clan was still there isn't it .'
T katni lh dang m u-tu wahh kur pyrtuh ki ynde
`so that's the truth about what's going on in our vill, so do you remember the year that this vill was estd.'
To t i-t toh wa tip i ka-daw ka wa jinglong jingman ka-ni ka-chnong yong i, t dp ni t t me kynmoo mi ma ai nadooh u-snm yee ma ai dp ki-sen ni ka-chnong sakhiat
`I don't remember the year, i just remember when my grandmother was carried here, they were the second to come and reside here.'
Kat ya u-snm t kynmoo o re khen phi, kat ya u-snm t nga wa khen hh i-yi t i-jingwanrah ya ka-t ka-beipun i chei-ni, t hawa man ong noh ki da man ki ki wa ar ki wan sohchnong hei-ni.
`I was just six years or so when my grandmother passed away, now I'm 65 years old, i remember slightly, she died when she was very old, just like my mother did.'

Tang kat na wa yap ka-beipun i lh nga jan ynru snm o mo, boi ym pu m o tang ynru snem, kat u-kynmoo eh o, t nga kattu la ynruphaw san snm o t, sniaw phi ka yap ko lh da tymmen da dor bha ko, kam wa yap hi ka-bei.
`I think it's in the 1800's, because the 1900's had gone.'
Jan na ki-snm khatphra spah hi, tharai neibhah u-ni u-snm khatkhynde spah da lai mo.
`my mother died when she was 92 years old, she was born here and her father was a pyrtuh.'
Tang kat kabei na wa yap ko lh ka la khyndephaw ar snm ko, ka da kha chei-ni ka u-pa ko u yong pyrtuh.
`I think it's in the 1800's, the hundred years had gone, ok we'll leave what was left behind.'
ka-snm khatphra spah hi jan, da ki-spah snm hi wa da lai, t i-eh ya ka t da lai kattu mo.
`so in this vill, who kept these forest.'
T yoo phi ha ka-ni ka-chnong sakhiat t ki-ni ki-khloo ki-kjam yee ma i wa booh tip hi mi'
`the vill as a whole or just the pyrtuh clan.'
ka-chnong waroh ka-wi ne mi ka-t ka-kur pyrtuh mo?
`no, what i knew was the forest here was managed by the elders, and as we know that the forest was made by the Creator.'
Che katkam wa tip o t, ya ka-chnong ka-khloo ka-kjam katkam wa tip wa pyllai ki-waheh t, ka-khloo t ong bait ka da man chwa ka wa booh u-t u-nongbooh nongthaw ya ka-t.
`the village as a whole as well as the clan managed the forest not only the village not only the clan'
Hadien da chim ka-chnong dp yn t t ya-kam lang ko ka-ryngkat wa ka-chnong wa ka-kur hi, ym m u-toh du ka-kur, ym toh du ka-chnong.
`everyone gave a hand and took care of it.'
yaksoh kti lang waroh hi, sumar lang.
`and whoever needed it was given, we share it.'
toh hi t t, Dep ni t t kat ka wa mkam lh ya u-yoh lang hi t mo.
`that's the most important thing for us to take care of it, especially today we should not destroy our forests around us.'

T to ka-t toh ka-wi ka-bynta ka wa mkam wa toh u-yasumar lang, khamtam ya ka-ni ka-pyrthai ka-mariang wa ka-ni ym hoi u-pynjot pyn-pra i ya ka-ni ka-khloo ka-kjam wan eh soodong ya ka-ni ka-chnong i. ynd?
`with regards to religions and chrisianity, who started it, was it really since the comings of the people from the west.'
T na liang ka-ni ka-niam ka-rukom kam ong noh ka-niam kristan, t sakhiat ya ka-ni ka-niam kristan toh m hi kong wa ong ki wa wan da ki t ka-ri sepngi ne chei-ni cha i-tip hi
`as i knew it was those people coming from the west.'
Nga katkam wa tip o t kam t, ong ki na ri sepngi wa wan chei-ni cha i neit.
`they convert people to Christianity, then afterwards different beliefs came up, like Mr Joy he started Chruch Of God, then came Roman Catholic and so on.'

Pynkylla kristan mo, o t jan toh hi, hadien hadien nei-t wa nang sen nangsen niam ki-t mo, kam ong noh t u-bah joy sen u ya ka-ni ka-niam Balang u-Blai, dep neit ka-niam Roman Catholic ter-ter kam t s ynde.
T jar jar ka-jingngait t kam t s mo.
`Q) `do you know that earlier we did have the traditional belief and custom before.'
T nang de sakhiat m ka-t ka-lh niam lh rukom ha i-tip hi mi mynchwa
Kat wa tip o hei-ni mynchwa,
yee ki ki-ni ki ong bait ki-t kam ka-jing..
`how did they perform the old/traditional culture.'
ka-culture ka wa rim tam t kammon lh ki
`the dancing, the pamkhla pamwait ceremony was there or not.'
ka-t ka-chad mastieh mo ka-t ka-pamkhla pamwait m mo ym m ko re marieh'
`as far as i know, there no such belief or ceremony because the hindu or non Christians at that time were just the pyrtuh clan and the khasis who resided in this vill.'

Nga kam wa tip o t chei-ni ha i-t m ko re ka-t bhah kat wa tip o t ki wa dang man hindu ki dang man chnong t du ki-ni ki yong pyrtuh hi wa ki-ni ki-khyriem ki wa wan sohchnong chei-ni cha chnong sohmynting.
`there's no such ceremony and dancing festivals like any other vill had.'
T ya ka-t ka-lhniam chad mastieh ka-t ka-won kawon kam ki-wi ki-chnong ki-bru t m ko re.
`but the pamblang (to cut the goat's neck with a dow 'the durga puja') ceremony was there during our childhood .'
Kat ya ka-t ka-pamblang ka-kna naai te m ko, jooh lai hi itai ha lyngdoh man i-por wa dang khynnah khian.
` is it true that there was this 'sniang blai (pig god) that the pyrtuh clan kept.'
T toh sakhiat hi nga sniaw kam wa ong ki wa m t u-sniang blai u wa ri ki yong pyrtuh wa bah ne m hi'
`yes, but i did not see him i just heard that he was there when we were just children'.'
Kat i-por yong i t nga ym m li-yoo o oo tang wa khana ki ong ki m hi u s, katt i-por i dang khynnah I.
Man u wa mane ki u t'
`I don't know but they said he was the 'sniang blai.'
Ym tip o wa mane mo kammon tang wa ong ki u-sniang blai ne.
`ok so that house was known as the 'iung blai', i heard about it it must be there only right .'
To, ya ka-t t man yung blai hi ko mo ka ka-yung kam ong nga jooh sniaw hi o wa ong ki ne man ka-t t kmai yung ko ne, jan hi t hi mo'

`yes there only, and there was this strange kind of plaintain that grew during that time, we were still young and haven't seen one like that, it never give birth to a another sapling, don't know what they called it..'
O hi t hi, wa ka-pachor m ka-tu ka-pachor ka-dooh ka-wi hi tu ha kmai yung, katt i-por i dang khynnah i t ka wa ym jooh yoo kha khon ko, ka wa dooh ka-wi bait ka-pachor yee khut ki kai ka-tu.
`who knows maybe it's the 'pachor blai' again, people during those times had beliefs in all kind of god.'
Tip ka-boi ka-pachor blai s ka-t lh, ong ki dang ngait blai.
`only one stem it has, in my childhood i used to have a look at it and wonder what kind of a plaintain was that, why would they just let it grow, it never had any saplings.'

tnung du ka-wi kat wa khliehsnem u-lipait ka lh ka-t ma ka-t man nga hadooh wa ong o mai ka-pachor yee re ka-kam ka-tu tip u-kha khon lh yoo hi re, yee yee lh m hi re kamte t ya u-khih ki re ka u-eh n.
`ok i think now the story telling is enough for today.'
To jan kattu da biang ka-t ka-jingyakhana parom t da biang noh chwa mo.
`if anyone of you know some stories come here..'
T la dang m ki-won ki-won wa tip parom t le.
un biang ka-chadien mo, hei-t i-por...
to, to, da hoi i, yap moo yoh jingmut
`I'll go back to the story, at that time when the phawa clan came to sohmynting, they asked for a place to built houses near pretty's house.'
hei-t i-por dang sdang wan ki-ni ki-phawa chei-ni cha samyntin, t pan ki-ni yong phawa hei-tai ha yung ka-pretty u-chna yung.
`they didn't let us, they said no it's not good to stay nearby, you people go down there, and then we got a nice location for building houses.'
T chah ki re I, ong ki chesh man re ya-chong lang, t phi chong chei-tai cha wah ya-jngai dp yn t poi ki-ni ki yong i chei-ni cha madan chnong da yoh i-thaw wa miat.
`earlier there was a fear, therefore if possible we want to stay together nearby everyone..'
Kam ong dang de t bhah kam ong phi t kam ong kat da man sohmynting t kat da ten ma yoh chirrup chirrup s hajan.
`but we were not allowed they told us go and stay over there, here near the village field..'
sniawsuk yachong yasah. Tangwa chah ko re ong ko phi chong chei-tai ne, chei-ni cha madan chnong.
`this good location was occupied by outsiders, whereas the natives (pyrtuh) settled in the hilly region..'
kat t i-ni i-thaw wa miat yoh ki u-chong ki wa nabar chnong mo, ki-t yn ki yong pyrtuh t chong ki cha khap loom khap wah eh.
`it was a small hill, at first it was a good spot too because the it seems cool, but nowadays it is not so good at all due to congestion..'
ka-loom ka wa rynchoin ne, ha ka-wi ka-liang yoo pyn-ngiat hi tangwa ha ki-ni ki-sngi t man ko ka-chnong man ko ka-thaw ka wa ym m u-miat, wa joor i-khynnia.
`Q) `you told us that when your grandma first came here she was back carried.'
hei-t i-por i wa ong phi ka-beipun yong phi wan nyngkong wan dei-bah'
`yes she was back carried by her brother and uncles..'
Oo, dei-bah ki-t ki-ma ki-woh ka s.
`Q) `when they first came here are they Christian.'
kat da wan ki da man kristan ki ne'
`no no not yet Christians, they were still non Christian..'
Ym pu m, ym pu m u-man kristan ki kat wa wan ki hei-ni, dang man chnong.
`when they were converted, they no longer be in contact with our clan from Tuber..'
T dp yn t t manda kylla kristan ki ym m de u-yatip wa ki-tai ki-kur wa wan ki na tuber.
`we were considered as a taboo by our clan from Tuber due to conversion..'
Sang ki-tai ki-kur i na Tuber wa da kylla kristan ki-ni ki yong i.
`q) `are you in contact prior to that.'
Kat wa ym pu m kylla dang yalai yawan phi'
`yes, even our grand uncle was lame, he went to tuber and was lame due to the disease called 'niangthoh',..'
O dang yalai yawan, te ste u-t u-woh soh i lh u-t wa tkoh u wa yoh niangthoh, ong ki ki wa yoh niangthoh cha tuber dei-bah.
`he was lame and he and the place was named as 'sohnok (is an expression for the way a lame person walk/limp)..'
dp t poi chitai yoh ka-niangthoh o, dp t tkoh u-pli ym hoi de, sohnok sohnok ne da mih wi naam wa ka-t ka-thaw man u-t u-sohnok ne, wa yoh niangthoh o t tkoh u.
`he lived on agriculture there, before all the cowboys said 'lets go to sohnok but the present generation children don't know about this..'
T li-rp soh u-pli hitu, kam ong katni khynnah ym tip de ki, dang hei-por chare masi i yoo phi t waroh khynnah chare masi ym pli beh masi cha sohnok.
`o, even i used to heard about it but i just don't know where is this place called 'sohnok..'
O nga lh jooh sniaw i-t wa khut pyrtuit ki s sohnok tangwa ym tip hei-won t i-thaw.
`he was lame and he just limp..'
Katwa tkoh u-pli nong t lai u-nok nok ne.
`now i know it's a person i thought its just a place..'
Hanpaya da u-bru mo, nga mut o i-t i-thaw ne.
`in olden days people used to named a place after a person..'
Ong bait dang de t e naam ki hi u-bru hi u-won u-won wa yee u-booh naam t toh kam t sah naam u s.
